scenes.title: Step 1
scenes.content: In octahedral symmetry, drag a unit length blue strut to the Z axis, make a ball at the midpoint then delete the strut and both endpoints, leaving just a ball at (0,0,1/2). Call that ball A.

scenes.title: Step 2
scenes.content: From ball A, drag a strut of custom length phi in the +X direction. Call the new ball B.

scenes.title: Step 3
scenes.content: From ball A, drag a strut of custom length 1/(-a+c) in the +Z direction. Call the new ball C.

scenes.title: Step 4
scenes.content: From ball A, drag a strut of custom length 1/(a+2c+e-2g) in the +Y direction. Call the new ball D.

scenes.title: Step 5
scenes.content: Switch to antiprism symmetry then select balls B and D.

scenes.title: Step 6
scenes.content: Apply the built-in "symmetry around red through origin" tool, deselect all, then select every 3rd ball on the outer ring, starting at ball B and every 6th ball around the inner ring starting at ball D.

scenes.title: Step 7
scenes.content:
Invert the selection, then delete, leaving 15 balls.
At this point, select all and save the file as the common starting point for J38 and J39.

scenes.title: Step 8 for J38
scenes.content: Either  use "Point Reflection" from the "Tools" menu to make the vertices of J38...

scenes.title: Step 8 for J39
scenes.content: ... or else use the built-in "reflection through XY plane" tool, then "Select All" to make the vertices of J39.

scenes.title: Step 9 for J38
scenes.content: In either case, use a 3D convex hull to generate the balls, struts and panels.

scenes.title: Step 9 for J39
scenes.content: In either case, use a 3D convex hull to generate the balls, struts and panels.
